<div class="amz" id="story5">
<!-- /wp:code -->

<!-- wp:cover {"url":"https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/Amazon_Underworld_ilustra_header-story6.jpg","id":164698,"dimRatio":0,"focalPoint":{"x":0.5,"y":0.09},"align":"full","className":"header-story"} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover alignfull header-story"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim-0 has-background-dim"></span><img class="wp-block-cover__image-background wp-image-164698" alt="" src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/Amazon_Underworld_ilustra_header-story6.jpg" style="object-position:50% 9%" data-object-fit="cover" data-object-position="50% 9%"/><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","placeholder":"Escreva o título...","fontSize":"large"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center has-large-font-size"></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164689,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6_lettering_EN.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-164689"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>By Bram Ebus</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When men who had arrived in his small Warakena Indigenous village in a distant corner of the Venezuelan Amazon offered him work driving a motorboat, Alexander* jumped at the chance. For the teenager, it was an opportunity to earn cash — a scarcity at the best of times, but especially since the economic collapse that had left Venezuela's currency, the Bolívar, nearly worthless.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“They told me that I was just going to work, to support my family,” he recalls of the men who took him to a camp in the forest several hours away, where he stayed for two months. But there was a catch.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“When I wanted to leave, I couldn’t, because they told me I was already part of the group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia. That’s when I started guerrilla life,” he says.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“I brought drugs from Colombia to Venezuela,” Alexander adds. “From Venezuela, they distribute the drugs by plane.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:code -->
