<!-- /wp:code -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Alexander’s tribe, the Warekena, of whom only a few hundred remain in Venezuela and northern Brazil, is among those threatened with violent displacement as their forests are razed for illegal gold mining and armed groups expand into their ancestral territories. UNESCO has warned that the Warakena language could disappear.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"32px"} -->
<div style="height:32px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164719,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6_icones_secretisland-e1691160137777.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-164719"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-a-secret-island-on-the-orinoco"><strong>A SECRET ISLAND ON THE ORINOCO</strong></h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>At first, the guerrilla fighters’ presence in the small Warakena community went unremarked, but they soon settled in and began giving orders, controlling who could enter and leave the area. They took charge of local justice and meted out punishments ranging from warnings to expulsion for offenses such as theft. They imposed some restrictions on fishing and patrolled the area with armed guards.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As the guerrillas grew bolder in luring Indigenous minors to their camps, a few dozen Warekena families saw only one option: escape. Alexander’s uncle, Francisco,* a 55-year-old Warakena leader, devised a plan. He organized what he said would be a community fishing trip on the Orinoco, but instead of returning home, the group settled on a small, rocky island, one of hundreds near the Colombian bank of the Orinoco River. Under blistering sun, the Warekena built their own refugee camp.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164701,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none","className":"border-full"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full border-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6-ft1.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-164701"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">A Warakena community moved from Venezuela to an island in the Orinoco River to escape guerrillas who were recruiting young people. | Photo credit: Bram Ebus</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>On a cloudy but sweltering morning, Francisco guided a dugout canoe along the edge of a flooded forest and beached it on a huge, worn rock outcrop that formed an island. A few steps away was his home: a shack cobbled together from mint green plastic tarps, garbage bags and driftwood.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Seated on a log, he described how Alexander, his nephew, had slowly got entrapped into guerrilla life in 2016. “First they took him on as a boat driver,” he says. “They gave his family food. They sweetened up his family. And finally, he stayed with them.”&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Francisco sees no likely end to the guerrilla occupation. “They’re not going to leave,” he says. Nevertheless, he adds dubiously, “Some of the things they do are good.“The guerrilla group pays teachers, whose government salary has plummeted, if they are paid at all. It helps with fuel to transport the sick to the hospital, and punishes thieves and violent offenders. Nevertheless, Francisco’s wife, overhearing her husband’s words as she preparess&nbsp; coffee over an open fire in front of the shack, disagrees.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“They’re bad,” she says, “because I know they take people's children.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164707,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none","className":"border-full"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full border-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6-ft3.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-164707"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><span data-metadata="<!--(figmeta)eyJmaWxlS2V5IjoiandTazhlVHVxZmdYcXhqSmhzdFlGMyIsInBhc3RlSUQiOjE2OTkyNTc5NTksImRhdGFUeXBlIjoic2NlbmUifQo=(/figmeta)-->"></span><span data-buffer="<!--(figma)(/figma)-->"></span>Their precarious new home on the rocky island offers the families some security, although they are still in guerrilla territory | Bram Ebus</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Three young men and two young women from their community went with the guerrillas, but only Alexander, sitting next to his uncle, returned. Two years after they fled their community, the families subsist on fish and on crops they grow in small garden patches.&nbsp; Life on the island is not easy, but Francisco is unwilling to stand by while the guerrillas snatch the community's young people away from their families.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“That’s why we came,” he says.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There's one nagging worry: their sanctuary still lies in guerrilla territory. Still, he sees the island as a haven for now.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“As long as I don't do anything wrong, I’m not afraid of anyone,” he says.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"32px"} -->
<div style="height:32px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164713,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6_icones_guerrillacamps-e1691160119323.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-164713"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-guerrilla-camps-a-mirage-of-luxury"><strong><strong>GUERRILLA CAMPS A MIRAGE OF LUXURY</strong></strong></h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>To young people in rural Amazonas, guerrilla groups offer the illusion of the good life, luring them with luxuries unheard of in their communities until they are past the point of no return.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Eusebio,* a 30-year Indigenous man from Amazonas, worked for both FARC dissidents and the ELN, driving motorboats that moved troops, drugs and weapons. Like Alexander, he started living in a guerrilla camp near his village, enjoying comforts he did not have at home.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"big"} -->
<p class="big">To young people in rural Amazonas, guerrilla groups offer the illusion of the good life, luring them with luxuries unheard of in their communities</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:cover {"customOverlayColor":"#d4c6ad","isDark":false,"align":"full","className":"tripa"} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover alignfull is-light tripa"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim-100 has-background-dim" style="background-color:#d4c6ad"></span><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:quote {"className":"main-content"} -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote main-content"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It's like a hotel. They have the best food there,” he says, grinning as he recalls the camp where he lived with about 100 others, in wooden houses they built themselves. There were refrigerators stocked with meat, doctors to tend the sick or injured, and satellite television via DirectTV. “They take it easy there, watching movies.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"16px"} -->
<div style="height:16px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The relative calm and safety of Venezuela, where the rebels are not pursued by government security forces, contrasts starkly with life in Colombia, where makeshift hideouts, set up quickly under the thick forest canopy before the sun sets, are part of the daily routine.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>And for those in Venezuela, the good life doesn't necessarily last. Guerrilla combatants are rotated every two months, and some are sent to Colombia, living under strict commanders and facing frequent combat. Colombian recruits, in turn, also pass through Venezuelan camps. “They're happy to get here,” Eusebio says. “Here you live like a king.”&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Alexander was recruited by the FARC when he was still a minor. He quickly became a combatant, was sent to Colombia, and rotated among combat units in conflict areas such as Guaviare, Arauca and Cauca—the latter some 900 kilometers (nearly 560 miles) from the Venezuelan border.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>And although conflict is rare on the Venezuelan side of the border, hostilities between the guerrillas and Venezuelan security forces do sometimes occur. According to Alexander, government troops from the border area who are stationed there “have relationships with the guerrillas. But those who come from [the interior of the country] don't. They come and fight.”&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:cover {"url":"https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/bloco1.png","id":164738,"dimRatio":0,"isDark":false} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover is-light"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim-0 has-background-dim"></span><img class="wp-block-cover__image-background wp-image-164738" alt="" src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/bloco1.png" data-object-fit="cover"/><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":164746,"width":111,"height":12,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/separador.png" alt="" class="wp-image-164746" width="111" height="12"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"big"} -->
<p class="big">The U.S. State Department has reported that Colombian guerrillas operate in Venezuela with “relative impunity” and accused the government of President Nicolás Maduro of complicity.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In 2019, concerns about ELN and FARC involvement in illegal gold mining led to sanctions by the U.S. Treasury Department. And in 2020, the U.S. Justice Department accused Maduro of conspiring with the FARC to “flood” the United States with cocaine.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In Amazonas, the ELN, which currently is in peace talks with the administration of Colombian President Gustavo Petro, with the Venezuelan government as a guarantor, quickly increased in size. One FARC dissident faction, the Acacio Medina front, which never signed the 2016 peace deal between the Colombian government and the FARC and therefore did not demobilize, has a longer history in the Venezuelan Amazon.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":164746,"width":111,"height":12,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/separador.png" alt="" class="wp-image-164746" width="111" height="12"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Alexander soon found that the good life was mostly mirage. Sometimes after he had been sent to collect “taxes,” or extortion payments, from illegal gold miners, a higher-ranking guerrilla would skim some of the money, leaving Alexander to take the blame.&nbsp; “If someone is doing well, they won't let him get ahead,” he says. “They keep trying to kill him until they succeed.”&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>FARC membership is usually for life, while the ELN allows members to leave under certain conditions. Forced recruitment is rare, however. With few options for earning money in their communities, and with food often in short supply, young people are easily tempted to go to the camps—if their fathers don’t send them first. Recruits are usually around age 15, though some are younger.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Like Alexander and Eusebio, they often start by doing odd jobs, like driving boats, which introduce them to the group. They train with a wooden imitation gun for about three months before receiving a real weapon.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:cover {"customOverlayColor":"#d4c6ad","isDark":false,"align":"full","className":"tripa"} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover alignfull is-light tripa"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim-100 has-background-dim" style="background-color:#d4c6ad"></span><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:quote {"className":"main-content"} -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote main-content"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“In my community, you'd see little kids with wooden guns. From the smallest to the biggest, they carry their wooden guns, playing,” Eusebio says. With three children to feed, he saw the guerrillas as his only opportunity. “I worked there out of need. That's why I worked with them.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"16px"} -->
<div style="height:16px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"16px"} -->
<div style="height:16px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164710,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6_icones_drughouses-e1691160109689.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-164710"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-drug-houses-everywhere"><strong><strong><strong>‘DRUG HOUSES EVERYWHERE’</strong></strong></strong></h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Venezuela is not a significant producer of coca, the raw material in cocaine. But as neighbor to Colombia, the world's largest coca producer, the country became a major cocaine exporter. It also is a processing center, with drug laboratories hidden under the forest canopy producing large amounts of cocaine destined for international markets.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“There were drug houses everywhere,” Eusebio says. “Those are houses where they store the drugs that go to Brazil.”&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Inhabitants of Amazonas are sometimes awakened by the sound of low-flying planes. Several sources, including Colombian law enforcement agents, local residents who lived among the guerrillas, and Eusebio and Alexander themselves, say that frequent cocaine flights depart to points in South and Central American countries such as Brazil and Panama. According to Alexander, the planes are loaded and fueled in the afternoon, then take off around 4 a.m. “They go out at night.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Eusebio moved cocaine to a clandestine airstrip two hours from his home community. “The guerrillas aren't the ones who carry the drugs. The guerrillas stand guard, load it into the plane, watch over it. The ones who carry the drugs are the traquetos.” he says, using a slang term for drug traffickers.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Cocaine laboratories are scattered throughout the Venezuelan state of Amazonas, the two Indigenous men say. When large quantities — hundreds of kilos — of drugs have been stockpiled, shipments leave, but not always by plane. Traquetos also embark on long journeys to smuggle the drugs to Brazil by boat.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:cover {"url":"https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/bg-green.jpg","id":160151,"dimRatio":50,"className":"tbranco"} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover tbranco"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim"></span><img class="wp-block-cover__image-background wp-image-160151" alt="" src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/bg-green.jpg" data-object-fit="cover"/><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","placeholder":"Escreva o título...","fontSize":"large"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center has-large-font-size">STATIC MAP<br>DRUG TRAFFICKING ROUTES AND CLANDESTINE AIRSTRIPS<br>laura</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Eusebio belonged to a group of about 10 traquetos who made frequent contraband trips. When one arrived at his destination, another would depart. Revenues from the shipments were shared by the FARC dissidents and the ELN, former rivals who now have a profit-sharing pact, he says.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>On his trips down the Río Negro toward the Brazilian town of São Gabriel de Cachoeira, he would be accompanied by around eight guerrillas armed with automatic rifles and sometimes wearing uniforms and red bandanas and flying a red and black flag.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&nbsp;“Once I took a shipment of 530 kilos [1,168 pounds],” Eusebio says. “There was marihuana, cocaine and various types of merchandise.” Venezuelan security forces, he adds, never stopped them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In Brazil, large crime syndicates take charge of the drugs, distributing to buyers throughout the country and exporting wholesale to Europe and Africa. But Eusebio says he never met with members of Brazilian drug gangs. Instead, he claims he handed the drugs over to rogue Brazilian law enforcement officials.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Before his boat reached São Gabriel de Cachoeira, three or four uniformed police officers would arrive, according to Eusebio.&nbsp; “They wait until dark to load it onto another boat,” he said.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Local media have reported on several cases of Brazilian law enforcement officials involved in drug trafficking in Amazonas. The region has seen a significant uptick in drug seizures and has become an important trafficking route since the COVID-19 pandemic.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":"48px"} -->
<div style="height:48px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164722,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6_icones_thelure-e1691160145539.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-164722"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-the-lure-of-illegal-economies"><strong><strong><strong><strong>THE LURE OF ILLEGAL ECONOMIES</strong></strong></strong></strong></h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Drug trafficking is not the Colombian guerrillas’ only lucrative business in Venezuela. Although mining was prohibited in Amazonas by presidential decree in 1989, illegal gold mines scar the forest in various parts of the state, including the border with Brazil and the flat-topped mountains known as tepuys, in Yapacana National Park.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>During his time with the guerrillas, one of Alexander's jobs was to collect protection money — known as a “vaccine” — from each mining claim in Yapacana National Park and an area called La Esmeralda.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“The fixed rule was one kilo of gold from each miner,” he says. “It has to be the full amount to hand it over to ‘El Viejo,’” the commander.&nbsp; If miners failed to pay, he had to take them to the commander, he says, adding,. “They killed some of them.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:cover {"url":"https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/bloco1.png","id":164738,"dimRatio":0,"isDark":false} -->
<div class="wp-block-cover is-light"><span aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim-0 has-background-dim"></span><img class="wp-block-cover__image-background wp-image-164738" alt="" src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/bloco1.png" data-object-fit="cover"/><div class="wp-block-cover__inner-container"><!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":164746,"width":111,"height":12,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/separador.png" alt="" class="wp-image-164746" width="111" height="12"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-on-the-trail-of-illegal-gold">On the trail of illegal gold</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>While some gold mined illegally in Venezuela is trafficked locally to Caracas or through Brazil, gold traffickers and law enforcement documents obtained by Amazon Underworld indicate that amounts varying from tens of grams to kilograms are smuggled to Colombia by way of the Atabapo River in soap bars or deodorant canisters, or in women’s bras or intimate parts.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It may be sold in gold shops in Puerto Inírida or taken on flights from the local airport, where one Colombian gold trafficker claimed police took bribes. One smuggler reported carrying five kilos of gold by way of the Vichada River to the town of Santa Rita, then by road to Medellín.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":164746,"width":111,"height":12,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/separador.png" alt="" class="wp-image-164746" width="111" height="12"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:cover -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The Colombian guerrillas have turned Amazonas into an economic powerhouse, financing operations in Colombia or elsewhere in Venezuela.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“They're no longer working for the people, as they say they are. They're in a war for drug-trafficking routes,” Alexander says. “Like some say, it's not about politics anymore. They're fighting for the coca routes, the mining and all that.”<br>The result is an economy that's hard for young people to resist.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“The lack of economic resources in Indigenous and mining areas has been the perfect opportunity for persuasive maneuvering by irregular groups, selling a policy of development and security,” one Indigenous teacher and community leader says. “At the same time, the fact that they handle large amounts of foreign currency has led to the acceptance of these irregular groups in communities and in mining areas, with the government's knowledge.”&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The guerrillas are lavish with gifts to young people. “They give them things — motorcycles, even food, and this puts them into debt,” says an education expert in the state of Amazonas.&nbsp; “The way to pay off the debt is to join them. Before they realize it, they're part of a criminal organization.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":164704,"sizeSlug":"full","linkDestination":"none","className":"border-full"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-full border-full"><img src="https://infoamazonia.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/story6-ft2.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-164704"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Doll’s arm lies on the ground on the Warakena community’s new island home | Bram Ebus</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In San Carlos de Río Negro, a small town on the banks of the river of the same name, which borders Colombia and connects with Brazil, most students have dropped out of school. In the 2020-2021 school year, 204 children enrolled, but 50 left for unknown reasons, another 50 were recruited by “irregular groups” and 34 went to work in gold mines. The next school year, only 70 children showed up.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A senior state official in Amazonas, who also requested anonymity, admits that many students and teachers abandoned school to work in the mines or join armed groups.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“There's government neglect and they get involved in these illegal activities,” he says, adding that the state lacks resources to visit communities that can be reached only by plane or by river, sometimes requiring weeks of travel.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>On the rocky island in the Orinoco River, Alexander, the young Warekena man, who is now in his 20s, knows he got lucky. When he was caught by the Colombian Navy on the Inírida River in that country, officials did not know what to do with an undocumented foreign rebel combatant who was a minor. A lieutenant told Alexander that he was too young to go to jail, and if he declared he had surrendered voluntarily, they would let him go free.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Seated on the log, Francisco, the community leader, looks at his nephew and sighs.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“I don't force them to stay, because they're legally adults,” he says of the community's oldest teenagers. He knows the move to the island did not change the conditions that drove Alexander and others like him to the guerrilla camps. The escape from their village is not a sustainable solution.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>He gazes over the river, toward the Venezuelan forest on the other side.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“The door is open,” he says.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

